This fleeting barrier is created when the moisture on the skin instantly vaporizes upon contact with the hot oil. While this might look like a superhuman feat, it’s a dangerous and fleeting trick relying more on physics than on fearlessness. description: Extremely rare white African wild dog puppy 4 Rivers is currently home to an extraordinary pack of wild dogs with a very leucistic pup. Local researchers have confirmed that this is extremely rare and virtually unheard of in Botswana for the past 30 years or so 🐾 In the 1990s, guides first spotted leucistic puppies in the Kwando area. The males of Kwando's pack have dispersed. These men, identified by photos, established a group dubbed the Golden Pack in the Vumbura area. Some descendants of this golden pack started another family in Kwara, where leucism was still evident but somewhat diluted. Leucism tends to be a lack of melanin in the skin, feathers, or hair. Melanin is the natural pigment responsible for most brown and black coloring. It is mostly genetic and varies in degree, going all the way to pure white in rare cases (like this one at 4 Rivers) or like in the "golden" Vumbura dogs, which are a pale tan tone. Currently, the pup interacts normally with its siblings and adult painted wolves (as African wild dogs are also known). Although this little one is anything but painted! If anything, it's dominant in the hierarchy when it comes to receiving food from adults! This pup may darken as he ages, and there is an outward chance that his whole body will be a large white spot, which sometimes happens with domestic dogs and cats. We'll keep a close eye to see how its color evolves 🐶 Thanks to the expert researchers in Botswana for their insight! Dr Peter Apps Dr John Tico McNutt Dr Gabriele Cozzi Botswana Predator Conservation

description: Another air hostess of Pakistan International Airlines (PIA) allegedly went missing while on duty in Canada. Sources privy to the matter said that upon investigation, a note expressing gratitude to PIA was discovered alongside her hanging uniform in her room which read out "Thank you, PIA." This marks the third reported case this year of PIA flight attendants allegedly 'slipping' while on duty, with two of them being women. Despite measures such as collecting passports of flight attendants assigned to Toronto flights to prevent such incidents, the effectiveness of these policies has come under scrutiny.
